WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.515 --> 00:00:02.932
(calm music)

2
00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:10.503
<v Dr. Weismiller>Okay, Dr. Levine is returning.</v>

3
00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:17.450
Everybody's favorite topic, management of chronic pain.

4
00:00:19.350 --> 00:00:22.350
Dr. Levine, please take it away, sir.

5
00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:23.853
<v ->Thank you, Dr. Weismiller.</v>

6
00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:28.560
Some references that you should be aware of.

7
00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:33.480
In 2016, CDC came up with some guidelines

8
00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:37.080
on how to prescribe opioids for chronic pain.

9
00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:40.830
They had 12 recommendations that applied to patients

10
00:00:40.830 --> 00:00:43.470
outside of active cancer treatment,

11
00:00:43.470 --> 00:00:46.740
palliative care, or end-of-life care.

12
00:00:46.740 --> 00:00:49.020
And they even came up with a nice little app

13
00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:53.043
that you could download and follow their advice.

14
00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:58.320
Well, they went ahead in 2022 and they changed

15
00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:02.580
some of those fairly minimally, but they updated them.

16
00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:04.950
They didn't update the app yet.

17
00:01:04.950 --> 00:01:07.650
But there are new guidelines available

18
00:01:07.650 --> 00:01:12.180
that are related to those 2016 CDC guidelines.

19
00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:15.480
CDC again tells you if you're gonna use the guidelines

20
00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:20.190
for adults for chronic non-cancer pain,

21
00:01:20.190 --> 00:01:22.500
there is no dosage cutoff for the use

22
00:01:22.500 --> 00:01:25.230
of opioids according to the guideline.

23
00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:29.430
They want you not to abruptly withdraw patients

24
00:01:29.430 --> 00:01:32.340
from opioids, especially on a high dose.

25
00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:35.400
And then if you have a patient with opioid use disorder,

26
00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:38.670
they want you to use medically-assisted therapy,

27
00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:42.543
not put them in a detox center and stop their medication.

28
00:01:43.530 --> 00:01:46.050
So remembering that, again, guidelines

29
00:01:46.050 --> 00:01:48.750
are not a replacement for clinical judgment.

30
00:01:48.750 --> 00:01:52.320
They're not intended to be inflexible standards of care,

31
00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:55.740
laws, regulations, or policies for us.

32
00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:58.230
Again, not applicable to sickle cell disease,

33
00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:01.530
cancer-related pain, palliative care,

34
00:02:01.530 --> 00:02:06.450
and they did not focus on opioids for opioid use disorder.

35
00:02:06.450 --> 00:02:09.273
So CDC wants us to make sure you know all that.

36
00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:13.110
There are also some guidelines that were put forth

37
00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:18.110
by the Federation of State Medical Boards, 2017.

38
00:02:18.480 --> 00:02:21.780
This is an organization that creates information

39
00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:24.930
for individual state medical boards.

40
00:02:24.930 --> 00:02:27.510
So the laws in your state relate to

41
00:02:27.510 --> 00:02:31.620
how you prescribe opioids probably came out of this

42
00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:33.480
particular set of guidelines.

43
00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:35.163
And we're gonna talk about those

44
00:02:35.163 --> 00:02:37.500
in a very short period of time.

45
00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:40.530
There's also information from the government

46
00:02:40.530 --> 00:02:44.340
specifically on best practices for pain management.

47
00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:46.623
So those are out there for you if you want.

48
00:02:47.580 --> 00:02:49.140
Now, what is pain?

49
00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:52.830
It's an unpleasant sensory and emotional experience

50
00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:55.380
associated with or resembling that

51
00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:58.470
associated with actual or potential damage.

52
00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:02.640
That's the definition from the IASP.

53
00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:05.040
Pain can be acute or chronic.

54
00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:08.730
Chronic pain can be neuropathic, mixed, nociceptive

55
00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:12.390
or visceral depending on its origin.

56
00:03:12.390 --> 00:03:14.760
Chronic pain is persistent pain,

57
00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:16.920
lasts for more than 12 weeks.

58
00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:21.060
No functional benefit from it and doesn't get better

59
00:03:21.060 --> 00:03:24.273
when the insult that created it gets better.

60
00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:28.410
How many people are out there with chronic pain?

61
00:03:28.410 --> 00:03:32.520
If you practice medicine, you know us on a day-to-day basis,

62
00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:35.940
10% to 30% of our population has chronic pain.

63
00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:39.990
7% has high impact pain that limits

64
00:03:39.990 --> 00:03:42.360
their work or life activities, and it's

65
00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:47.360
the most common reason people come to see you is pain.

66
00:03:48.570 --> 00:03:50.040
If you think about some of the things

67
00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:52.350
you see in your typical clinical practice

68
00:03:52.350 --> 00:03:56.430
that cause pain, you know, back pain is right up there,

69
00:03:56.430 --> 00:03:58.200
arthritis is right up there,

70
00:03:58.200 --> 00:04:00.780
chronic headaches are right up there.

71
00:04:00.780 --> 00:04:03.930
Not sure why osteoporosis is on this list

72
00:04:03.930 --> 00:04:05.100
other than for fractures.

73
00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:06.993
Those people don't really have pain.

74
00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:12.690
Diabetic neuropathy, fibromyalgia, the dreaded fibromyalgia

75
00:04:12.690 --> 00:04:14.640
actually pretty low in terms of

76
00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:17.163
how many people are afflicted.

77
00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:20.880
So our first question for you,

78
00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:23.880
which of the following statements is correct?

79
00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:27.660
Depression is commonly associated with chronic pain.

80
00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:31.443
On numerical pain scale, 10 represents true happiness.

81
00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:35.190
The Federation of State Medical Boards mandates

82
00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:38.730
consultation with a pain management specialist for patients

83
00:04:38.730 --> 00:04:42.420
receiving chronic opioid therapy for chronic pain.

84
00:04:42.420 --> 00:04:46.290
And allodynia is an elevated pain response

85
00:04:46.290 --> 00:04:47.583
to a painful stimulus.

86
00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:50.433
So which one of those is correct?

87
00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:58.290
And if you practice, you know that A is correct

88
00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:01.293
'cause we see this constantly all the time.

89
00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:06.450
There are two terms in patients with chronic pain

90
00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:07.410
you need to be aware of.

91
00:05:07.410 --> 00:05:09.630
These could show up in the boards.

92
00:05:09.630 --> 00:05:14.630
Hyperalgesia is when you create a painful stimulus

93
00:05:14.670 --> 00:05:16.800
and you get an elevated pain response

94
00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:19.863
from the patient more so than you would expect.

95
00:05:20.820 --> 00:05:24.450
Allodynia is a non-painful stimulus

96
00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:28.143
that produces a painful response by the patient.

97
00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:34.830
Depression, highly associated with chronic pain.

98
00:05:34.830 --> 00:05:37.590
Anxiety, insomnia, weight loss,

99
00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:39.720
just a poor quality of life in people

100
00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.303
who have to struggle with that on a regular basis.

101
00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:45.180
You know, all of us were not trained

102
00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:47.223
to be pain management specialists.

103
00:05:48.390 --> 00:05:51.750
It's not easy to objectively assess pain.

104
00:05:51.750 --> 00:05:54.570
There's no blood test for that obviously.

105
00:05:54.570 --> 00:05:56.310
Guidelines are coming and going.

106
00:05:56.310 --> 00:06:00.060
We all worry about controlled substances and addiction

107
00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:03.660
and contributing to overdose and side effect management.

108
00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:07.050
So it's not easy to manage pain.

109
00:06:07.050 --> 00:06:09.480
That's why we have pain management specialists to help us

110
00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:11.883
with that often when they're available.

111
00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:14.820
How do you assess pain?

112
00:06:14.820 --> 00:06:17.340
You can ask the patient, how bad is it

113
00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:20.400
from no pain to the worst possible pain.

114
00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:23.760
You know, how did it feel when you went through childbirth?

115
00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:26.643
Which works well for women, but not necessarily for men.

116
00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.080
Ask on a pain scale of zero to 10,

117
00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:32.970
10 as the worst possible pain.

118
00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:36.123
Well doc, it's over 14.

119
00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:40.380
A lot of those, you can show 'em a funny face

120
00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:43.113
or a frowny face, gets last, doesn't help a lot.

121
00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:45.870
There is some truth to the fact

122
00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:48.270
that patients from ethnic minorities

123
00:06:48.270 --> 00:06:51.840
and cultures different from the provider treating them

124
00:06:51.840 --> 00:06:54.930
are at risk for receiving inadequate pain management.

125
00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:56.163
So be aware of that.

126
00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:01.830
I mentioned the federation medical board's guidelines.

127
00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:03.540
I'll go through some of them

128
00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:05.550
because if you follow these guidelines,

129
00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:08.490
you're probably gonna be in compliance

130
00:07:08.490 --> 00:07:10.410
with your state's guidelines as well.

131
00:07:10.410 --> 00:07:12.240
And they're pretty simple.

132
00:07:12.240 --> 00:07:13.950
Know that when you treat chronic pain,

133
00:07:13.950 --> 00:07:18.120
you treat it in the context of a reason for it.

134
00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:20.100
So you're not just gonna treat pain,

135
00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:21.840
you're gonna treat a patient.

136
00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:24.930
You're gonna examine them, you're gonna talk to them,

137
00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:27.900
you're gonna do an evaluation for why they're hurting

138
00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:30.150
and you wanna make sure that it's documented.

139
00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:33.960
You wanna make sure that you assess their alcohol

140
00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:36.720
or medication misuse risk.

141
00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:38.460
You wanna review the state's

142
00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:41.640
Prescription Drug Monitoring Program.

143
00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:44.160
As of two years ago, there was one state

144
00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:48.630
that didn't have one, Missouri, which is now in compliance.

145
00:07:48.630 --> 00:07:51.750
So all states now have one of those things.

146
00:07:51.750 --> 00:07:53.670
You wanna screen your patients for depression

147
00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:56.103
because the association is so high.

148
00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:00.810
When you treat the patient, document their response.

149
00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:03.150
How are they doing with the treatment?

150
00:08:03.150 --> 00:08:06.390
And monitor their effectiveness each time you see 'em.

151
00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:09.120
And you can use the five A's for that.

152
00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:11.940
There are five A's for a lot of different conditions,

153
00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:14.700
but as it relates to chronic pain management,

154
00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:18.330
it's analgesia, their activities of daily living,

155
00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:21.240
and the adverse effects from their medication,

156
00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:25.410
any aberrant drug taking behaviors that you identify,

157
00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:28.440
and how that patient affect is doing

158
00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:30.093
during this treatment process.

159
00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:34.410
The medical board's guidelines recommend

160
00:08:34.410 --> 00:08:37.680
that you document a signed, written informed consent

161
00:08:37.680 --> 00:08:40.350
and treatment agreement, and we'll go over those

162
00:08:40.350 --> 00:08:42.513
in more detail later as well.

163
00:08:43.470 --> 00:08:47.070
You want to do periodic random drug testing.

164
00:08:47.070 --> 00:08:49.890
That doesn't mean, "Mr. Smith, when you come in next time,

165
00:08:49.890 --> 00:08:51.447
we're gonna check your urine."

166
00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:55.020
It means random.

167
00:08:55.020 --> 00:08:58.500
And if you check a urine, it comes back abnormal,

168
00:08:58.500 --> 00:08:59.850
the expectation is you're gonna do

169
00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:02.040
something about it, not just leave it,

170
00:09:02.040 --> 00:09:03.663
sit there in the medical record.

171
00:09:04.620 --> 00:09:08.190
You wanna record all your treatments, your prescriptions,

172
00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:11.100
and have the patient return appropriate intervals

173
00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:13.380
for evaluation more frequently

174
00:09:13.380 --> 00:09:14.970
when you're starting treatment.

175
00:09:14.970 --> 00:09:17.250
You know, how frequent should it be?

176
00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:19.380
Probably if you're doing it every three months,

177
00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:21.720
you're probably very reasonable.

178
00:09:21.720 --> 00:09:23.490
Stable patients, maybe less often,

179
00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:25.830
unstable patients, more often.

180
00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:27.930
But you want to continue to see them back.

181
00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:31.140
If your patient's difficult,

182
00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:33.900
then you might want to see consultation.

183
00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:35.670
There are pain management experts

184
00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:40.050
who initially were anesthesiologists, psychiatrists,

185
00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:41.940
those who are borne to addiction medicine,

186
00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:44.400
mental health specialists, a lot of people

187
00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:46.503
that can help you in this process.

188
00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:52.530
Our second question, which of the following statements

189
00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:56.310
regarding pharmacotherapy in chronic pain is true?

190
00:09:56.310 --> 00:09:59.610
Nonpharmacologic therapy and nonopioid

191
00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:01.920
pharmacologic therapy are preferred

192
00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:03.453
for chronic pain management.

193
00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:08.580
Neuroleptic malignant syndrome is a concerning side effect

194
00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:12.017
when you combine tramadol and cyclobenzaprine.

195
00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:16.170
TCA antidepressants have not been shown

196
00:10:16.170 --> 00:10:19.650
to be effective in the treatment of diabetic neuropathy.

197
00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:22.620
And SSRIs are effective in treating the pain

198
00:10:22.620 --> 00:10:24.453
of postherpetic neuralgia.

199
00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:32.310
And you voted for the first one.

200
00:10:32.310 --> 00:10:35.940
Nonpharmacologic therapy, nonopioid pharmacologic therapy

201
00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:38.790
are preferred for chronic pain

202
00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:41.250
and this comes right out of the CDC's guidelines.

203
00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:44.970
Number one, top of the list.

204
00:10:44.970 --> 00:10:48.120
They say nonopioid therapies are at least as effective

205
00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:52.080
as opioids for many types of acute pain.

206
00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:55.743
And the clinician should maximize those nonopioid therapies.

207
00:10:57.420 --> 00:11:00.330
And then moving to subacute and chronic pain,

208
00:11:00.330 --> 00:11:02.673
basically the same statements.

209
00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:05.970
Okay, we have a lot of modalities

210
00:11:05.970 --> 00:11:07.860
we can use for chronic pain.

211
00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:10.830
We have physical modalities, nonpharmacologic

212
00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:14.010
behavioral therapies, pharmacologic therapies,

213
00:11:14.010 --> 00:11:18.153
neural blockades, even devices that we implant in people.

214
00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:22.170
And what are some of the nonpharmacologic things?

215
00:11:22.170 --> 00:11:26.430
Acupuncture's out there, physical therapy is out there,

216
00:11:26.430 --> 00:11:31.430
osteopathic manipulation, chiropractic, massage therapy,

217
00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:35.973
ultrasound and spinal cord stimulation are out there.

218
00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:40.170
Acupuncture has been shown to be helpful

219
00:11:40.170 --> 00:11:44.370
in things like chronic neck pain, low back pain,

220
00:11:44.370 --> 00:11:47.673
DJD, headaches, even fibromyalgia.

221
00:11:49.410 --> 00:11:52.020
What about nonpharmacologic behavioral treatments?

222
00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:54.690
Cognitive behavioral therapy,

223
00:11:54.690 --> 00:11:57.960
mindfulness, relaxation, meditation.

224
00:11:57.960 --> 00:11:59.370
What would you rather be doing

225
00:11:59.370 --> 00:12:02.040
than being here today particularly?

226
00:12:02.040 --> 00:12:02.873
Sleep.

227
00:12:02.873 --> 00:12:04.830
Sleep is incredibly important

228
00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:07.293
in treating patients with chronic pain.

229
00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:11.520
Now, if you're gonna use drugs, not you personally,

230
00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:14.460
if you're gonna use them in treating patients,

231
00:12:14.460 --> 00:12:17.190
start with monotherapy if possible.

232
00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:19.710
Titrate one drug at a time.

233
00:12:19.710 --> 00:12:22.713
Your goal is not necessarily to get rid of all that pain,

234
00:12:22.713 --> 00:12:26.370
it's to improve it, to improve their function

235
00:12:26.370 --> 00:12:28.560
while limiting side effects, and knowing that

236
00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:30.510
not everybody reacts the same way,

237
00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:33.870
the same things that you might try for somebody else.

238
00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:35.883
So you have to individualize things.

239
00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:40.020
With our pharmacologic agents, we kind of have a pyramid.

240
00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:41.490
We start at the bottom.

241
00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:45.420
Acetaminophen for most folks, moving up into NSAIDs,

242
00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:47.610
both traditional and Cox-2,

243
00:12:47.610 --> 00:12:50.640
they have the same analgesic effects essentially.

244
00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:54.000
There are adjuvant agents available to us.

245
00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.400
Then there are kind of semi-opioids

246
00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:58.830
like tramadol and tapentadol,

247
00:12:58.830 --> 00:13:01.983
and then there are the more classical opioids that we have.

248
00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:08.420
Adjuvant agents include SNRIs and TCAs.

249
00:13:08.460 --> 00:13:12.810
Anticonvulsants are centrally acting agents like clonidine.

250
00:13:12.810 --> 00:13:17.430
Muscle relaxants and even topical anesthetics.

251
00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:21.360
The TCAs we use include amitriptyline and nortriptyline.

252
00:13:21.360 --> 00:13:24.330
Remember, they're quite anticholinergic

253
00:13:24.330 --> 00:13:26.190
and have those side effects.

254
00:13:26.190 --> 00:13:30.843
SNRIs are good for pain, SSRIs are not.

255
00:13:32.100 --> 00:13:35.860
Duloxetine, milnacipran, venlafaxine,

256
00:13:35.860 --> 00:13:40.680
desvenlafaxine are available to help us.

257
00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:42.630
If you look at some of the effectiveness

258
00:13:42.630 --> 00:13:46.020
of our antidepressants in chronic pain,

259
00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:47.340
the best effectiveness is

260
00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:50.160
in their treatment of diabetic neuropathies

261
00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:52.833
and not quite as good for fibromyalgia.

262
00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:55.890
Anticonvulsants.

263
00:13:55.890 --> 00:13:58.740
We've used those for pain for quite a while.

264
00:13:58.740 --> 00:14:02.310
You know, carbamazepine for tic douloureux,

265
00:14:02.310 --> 00:14:04.770
trigeminal neuralgia for years.

266
00:14:04.770 --> 00:14:08.250
Depakote's out there, gabapentin, pregabalin,

267
00:14:08.250 --> 00:14:12.120
and in Topamax used for chronic pain.

268
00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:16.560
Clonidine, other centrally acting alpha-adrenergic agents

269
00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:19.593
are useful for a number of different modalities.

270
00:14:22.290 --> 00:14:25.110
Muscle relaxants like cyclobenzaprine,

271
00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:28.440
carisoprodol, methocarbamol.

272
00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:31.500
We're seeing a lot of methocarbamol use in our area.

273
00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:32.820
I'm not sure why.

274
00:14:32.820 --> 00:14:34.113
Often by surgeons.

275
00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:36.960
Carisoprodol or Soma.

276
00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:41.700
Watch out for patients who are dependent on those

277
00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:44.520
and may withdraw if you stop 'em abruptly.

278
00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:47.220
They are sedating, tend to work better

279
00:14:47.220 --> 00:14:51.510
before sleep to help people rest as well as help their pain.

280
00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:56.510
Tramadol is a weak mu opioid receptor agonist.

281
00:14:56.670 --> 00:15:01.670
Is also weak SNRI, so it has some antidepressant properties.

282
00:15:01.729 --> 00:15:06.729
If you use it in conjunction with other serotonin agents,

283
00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:09.060
you can get a serotonin syndrome,

284
00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:11.310
not a neuroleptic malignant syndrome

285
00:15:11.310 --> 00:15:13.110
that was in your question.

286
00:15:13.110 --> 00:15:15.660
And it does lower seizure threshold.

287
00:15:15.660 --> 00:15:18.900
Tapentadol, fairly similar to tramadol,

288
00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:20.940
but a little stronger analgesic.

289
00:15:20.940 --> 00:15:24.273
A little weaker SSRI effect.

290
00:15:26.310 --> 00:15:28.833
What about marijuana and chronic pain?

291
00:15:29.970 --> 00:15:33.540
Well, cannabis has certain chemicals

292
00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:35.040
that are associated with it.

293
00:15:35.040 --> 00:15:40.040
THC gives you your high, CBD, not typically intoxicating.

294
00:15:41.190 --> 00:15:42.870
There are synthetic cannabinoids

295
00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:44.280
that we've used in practice.

296
00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:46.923
Dronabinol and abalone for example.

297
00:15:48.180 --> 00:15:49.950
So those are out there.

298
00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:51.320
You know, what about chronic pain

299
00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:55.410
or what about indications for using cannabis?

300
00:15:55.410 --> 00:15:58.620
Well, there are some indications for using it in seizure,

301
00:15:58.620 --> 00:16:01.230
giving seizure disorders with nausea,

302
00:16:01.230 --> 00:16:03.630
vomiting, and chemotherapy.

303
00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:07.290
In anorexia, weight loss, AIDs patients,

304
00:16:07.290 --> 00:16:10.110
spasticity, multiple sclerosis.

305
00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:11.970
There's some good data on that.

306
00:16:11.970 --> 00:16:13.740
There's also some data on usefulness

307
00:16:13.740 --> 00:16:15.930
and a myriad of other conditions,

308
00:16:15.930 --> 00:16:19.170
but the data is not as robust or as strong,

309
00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:21.663
but chronic pain is, in fact, one of those.

310
00:16:22.830 --> 00:16:25.350
There was an article in the board's own journal

311
00:16:25.350 --> 00:16:27.120
back about 10 years ago.

312
00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:30.153
It talked about some of the benefits of cannabis.

313
00:16:31.830 --> 00:16:36.630
Here's some others that came a little bit less in the past,

314
00:16:36.630 --> 00:16:39.933
the more in the recent ones as well.

315
00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:44.790
And again, there's some data to support it.

316
00:16:44.790 --> 00:16:47.610
If you look at the map of medical marijuana,

317
00:16:47.610 --> 00:16:50.400
Wikipedia does one of these every year,

318
00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:53.520
and these maps are filling in more with green

319
00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:57.450
and blue as states decide to allow

320
00:16:57.450 --> 00:16:59.433
medical marijuana and marijuana use.

321
00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:06.360
Where we stand today, it's a map that continues to evolve.

322
00:17:06.360 --> 00:17:09.390
It's a therapy that continues to evolve.

323
00:17:09.390 --> 00:17:11.130
I think we're finding more uses for it.

324
00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:13.560
We're also seeing more issues with it.

325
00:17:13.560 --> 00:17:15.900
So kind of keep your eyes and ears open

326
00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:18.330
to what use in your community

327
00:17:18.330 --> 00:17:20.080
and what you feel comfortable with.

328
00:17:24.090 --> 00:17:26.910
Which of the following statements is true?

329
00:17:26.910 --> 00:17:29.730
Topical analgesics are not typically associated

330
00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:33.120
with systemic side effects in drug interactions.

331
00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:36.390
The dose of topical diclofenac is higher

332
00:17:36.390 --> 00:17:39.360
for treating osteoarthritis in the upper extremity

333
00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:42.570
than the dose you would use in the lower extremity.

334
00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:46.710
EMLA cream, mixing lidocaine and diphenhydramine,

335
00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:50.700
is FDA approved for the topical treatment of pain.

336
00:17:50.700 --> 00:17:54.720
And finally, lidocaine 5% patch is effective when applied

337
00:17:54.720 --> 00:17:57.723
anywhere in the body, not just over the site of pain.

338
00:18:03.146 --> 00:18:05.790
And you've chosen the first one, which is correct.

339
00:18:05.790 --> 00:18:07.530
These agents do not typically get

340
00:18:07.530 --> 00:18:10.860
too many side effects or drug interactions.

341
00:18:10.860 --> 00:18:13.350
Topical agents act within the skin,

342
00:18:13.350 --> 00:18:15.180
adjacent peripheral nerves.

343
00:18:15.180 --> 00:18:17.670
You don't get much in the way of serum levels,

344
00:18:17.670 --> 00:18:20.610
so they're relatively, but not totally free

345
00:18:20.610 --> 00:18:24.090
of systemic side effects or drug interactions.

346
00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:27.690
Some of the ones we have are salicylate related.

347
00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:30.480
Diclofenac is out there.

348
00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:32.610
If you use that, the dose is dependent

349
00:18:32.610 --> 00:18:33.840
on the size of the joints,

350
00:18:33.840 --> 00:18:36.210
so typically smaller, upper extremities,

351
00:18:36.210 --> 00:18:38.910
larger, lower extremities.

352
00:18:38.910 --> 00:18:42.900
Capsaicin is used for neuropathic pain.

353
00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:46.600
EMLA is actually a combination of lidocaine and prilocaine

354
00:18:47.490 --> 00:18:50.730
and we use that before we poke kids

355
00:18:50.730 --> 00:18:54.990
for blood draws and lumbar punctures and procedures.

356
00:18:54.990 --> 00:18:59.730
It's not for pain, it's to reduce subsequent pain.

357
00:18:59.730 --> 00:19:02.213
And then we have our Lidoderm patches.

358
00:19:02.213 --> 00:19:05.970
5% is the prescription, I think 4% and others

359
00:19:05.970 --> 00:19:07.420
you can get over the counter.

360
00:19:08.370 --> 00:19:11.280
When you use the Lidoderm patch, you can use 'em

361
00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:13.860
up to three patches at a time.

362
00:19:13.860 --> 00:19:16.110
They're about 12 hours in duration.

363
00:19:16.110 --> 00:19:18.120
You can cut 'em if you need 'em

364
00:19:18.120 --> 00:19:20.320
and you wanna put 'em over the site of pain.

365
00:19:21.960 --> 00:19:26.040
There's efficacy, good efficacy for postherpetic neuralgia

366
00:19:26.040 --> 00:19:27.450
and that's where insurance companies

367
00:19:27.450 --> 00:19:29.400
will pay you for it reliably.

368
00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:32.250
They don't pay for it reliably for a lot of other things.

369
00:19:33.300 --> 00:19:36.150
Moving on to talk about opioids.

370
00:19:36.150 --> 00:19:37.350
When was the first time

371
00:19:37.350 --> 00:19:39.783
that you remember hearing about opioids?

372
00:19:41.700 --> 00:19:45.750
Do you remember as a young person watching a movie

373
00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:49.110
where a bunch of travelers came up on a yellow road

374
00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:53.520
over a hillside and saw this green city in front of them

375
00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:56.400
and that hillside was full of flowers

376
00:19:56.400 --> 00:19:58.503
where they promptly fell asleep?

377
00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:01.551
And what were those flowers?

378
00:20:01.551 --> 00:20:02.384
<v Audience>Poppies.</v>

379
00:20:02.384 --> 00:20:03.630
<v ->Poppies.</v>

380
00:20:03.630 --> 00:20:06.063
Yeah, poppies.

381
00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:12.393
Which of the following statements regarding opioids is true?

382
00:20:13.530 --> 00:20:15.810
Opioids have been shown to be highly effective

383
00:20:15.810 --> 00:20:18.960
for non-cancer related chronic pain.

384
00:20:18.960 --> 00:20:22.950
A realistic goal of opioid therapy is complete pain relief.

385
00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:26.070
It's unnecessary to identify individuals at risk

386
00:20:26.070 --> 00:20:29.160
for substance abuse prior to beginning opioids.

387
00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:31.890
And if opioids are prescribed for chronic pain,

388
00:20:31.890 --> 00:20:33.780
begin treatment with immediate acting

389
00:20:33.780 --> 00:20:36.150
rather than extended-release preparations

390
00:20:36.150 --> 00:20:38.343
and then titrate to optimal effect.

391
00:20:44.040 --> 00:20:46.500
All right, D, D is correct.

392
00:20:46.500 --> 00:20:47.700
D is correct.

393
00:20:47.700 --> 00:20:52.700
Start with immediate acting and then titrate them to effect.

394
00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:54.630
We are in the midst and have been

395
00:20:54.630 --> 00:20:57.243
for a while in opioid epidemic.

396
00:20:58.260 --> 00:21:00.570
Half a million or more people died

397
00:21:00.570 --> 00:21:05.040
from opioid overdose just 1999.

398
00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:07.803
A lot, and it continues to get bigger unfortunately.

399
00:21:08.760 --> 00:21:12.570
There are waves of opioids used in this epidemic.

400
00:21:12.570 --> 00:21:16.320
Earlier, there were prescription drugs like OxyContin.

401
00:21:16.320 --> 00:21:18.060
More recently it's fentanyl

402
00:21:18.060 --> 00:21:20.463
in combination with amphetamines.

403
00:21:21.600 --> 00:21:24.780
The overdose death rates however parallel are increased

404
00:21:24.780 --> 00:21:27.453
in prescription analgesic drug sales.

405
00:21:28.350 --> 00:21:31.170
And a drug overdose now the leading cause

406
00:21:31.170 --> 00:21:34.500
of accidental deaths in adults in the US

407
00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:36.930
in more than half of our states.

408
00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:39.993
And motor vehicle accidents being number two.

409
00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:43.563
Unfortunately still a problem for us,

410
00:21:44.430 --> 00:21:46.890
so we need to use them wisely.

411
00:21:46.890 --> 00:21:48.930
There is good evidence for effectiveness

412
00:21:48.930 --> 00:21:51.243
of opioids in cancer-related pain.

413
00:21:53.100 --> 00:21:55.560
What about chronic non-cancer pain?

414
00:21:55.560 --> 00:21:59.340
Weak, weak evidence both in Cochrane review

415
00:21:59.340 --> 00:22:02.370
and some other studies as well.

416
00:22:02.370 --> 00:22:05.520
In fact, patients with chronic diffuse pain

417
00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:09.210
like your fibromyalgias, your chronic pelvic pains,

418
00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:11.610
much less likely to benefit, much more likely

419
00:22:11.610 --> 00:22:14.913
to be harmed when you treat them with opioids.

420
00:22:16.500 --> 00:22:18.180
CDC's guideline number two,

421
00:22:18.180 --> 00:22:20.700
before you start opioid therapy,

422
00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:23.940
discuss with patients benefits and risks.

423
00:22:23.940 --> 00:22:26.520
Establish treatment goals and consider

424
00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:29.550
how the therapy will be stopped if benefits

425
00:22:29.550 --> 00:22:31.650
don't outweigh your risk.

426
00:22:31.650 --> 00:22:33.420
Remember, complete pain relief,

427
00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:36.030
rarely achieved, may not be the goal,

428
00:22:36.030 --> 00:22:39.840
but improved function is, pain reduction is,

429
00:22:39.840 --> 00:22:43.020
improved mood, improved ability to work.

430
00:22:43.020 --> 00:22:44.793
Those are realistic goals.

431
00:22:45.630 --> 00:22:48.690
Before doing opioid therapy for your patient,

432
00:22:48.690 --> 00:22:52.530
look at other treatable pain generators.

433
00:22:52.530 --> 00:22:55.140
Use physical and psychological modalities.

434
00:22:55.140 --> 00:23:00.140
Help them rest better, treat their associated mood disorders

435
00:23:00.240 --> 00:23:02.670
and use nonopioid analgesics.

436
00:23:02.670 --> 00:23:05.883
If they don't work, there you go with your opioids.

437
00:23:06.900 --> 00:23:09.570
When you start therapy with opioids,

438
00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:11.730
get an agreement in place.

439
00:23:11.730 --> 00:23:15.330
Consider the initial 90 days sort of therapeutic trial.

440
00:23:15.330 --> 00:23:19.080
Begin short acting agents, titrate them up.

441
00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:21.540
Be proactive with side effects.

442
00:23:21.540 --> 00:23:23.940
Figure they're probably gonna get constipated.

443
00:23:23.940 --> 00:23:26.540
Talk to them about how to avoid that and treat that.

444
00:23:28.140 --> 00:23:31.080
Screen them at onset for inappropriate drugs

445
00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:33.510
at least yearly, and reassess them.

446
00:23:33.510 --> 00:23:34.790
Are they doing well with it?

447
00:23:34.790 --> 00:23:37.050
If not, they having issues?

448
00:23:37.050 --> 00:23:38.133
Do I need to stop?

449
00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:42.330
When you start, again, immediate release opioids

450
00:23:42.330 --> 00:23:44.703
instead of extended release opioids.

451
00:23:47.310 --> 00:23:48.690
Review the patient's history

452
00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:51.900
of controlled substances with the registry.

453
00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:53.310
Make sure you do that.

454
00:23:53.310 --> 00:23:56.730
They're not getting medicines from different sources.

455
00:23:56.730 --> 00:24:01.260
Check their risk for problems related to opioid use.

456
00:24:01.260 --> 00:24:04.110
There's an opioid risk tool out there.

457
00:24:04.110 --> 00:24:05.550
The best way to find this is

458
00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:07.920
to use my favorite medical website,

459
00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:12.690
www.google.com, type in opioid risk tool,

460
00:24:12.690 --> 00:24:14.643
and 17 will show up for you.

461
00:24:18.990 --> 00:24:22.500
Which of the following statements regarding opioids is true?

462
00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:26.250
There are three opioid receptors, phi, beta and kappa.

463
00:24:26.250 --> 00:24:28.920
When prescribing opioids for acute pain,

464
00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:32.580
more than seven days supply will rarely be needed.

465
00:24:32.580 --> 00:24:36.810
Oxycodone is roughly three times as potent as morphine.

466
00:24:36.810 --> 00:24:39.060
And transdermal fentanyl is indicated

467
00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:41.823
for acute and post-op pain management.

468
00:24:47.010 --> 00:24:50.520
You have decided B, and B in fact is correct.

469
00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:54.000
Usually don't need more than seven days of therapy.

470
00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:57.060
There are three opioid receptor classes,

471
00:24:57.060 --> 00:24:59.673
mu, kappa and delta.

472
00:25:01.230 --> 00:25:04.230
When opioids are initiated, again,

473
00:25:04.230 --> 00:25:07.353
start with the lowest effective dose.

474
00:25:08.490 --> 00:25:12.580
Usually only for the expected duration of pain

475
00:25:14.310 --> 00:25:17.670
and that's gonna be three days or less for most people

476
00:25:17.670 --> 00:25:19.590
and rarely will you need more than

477
00:25:19.590 --> 00:25:23.130
a week's worth for acute pain.

478
00:25:23.130 --> 00:25:25.140
What are some short-acting opioids?

479
00:25:25.140 --> 00:25:29.300
There's morphine, codeine, hydrocodone, oxycodone,

480
00:25:29.300 --> 00:25:34.300
hydromorphone, oxymorphone, fentanyl are a few of them.

481
00:25:34.620 --> 00:25:37.260
Long-acting opioids include methadone,

482
00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:40.650
the sustained-release products of morphine, oxycodone,

483
00:25:40.650 --> 00:25:44.340
hydromorphone, your buprenorphine, naloxone

484
00:25:44.340 --> 00:25:46.350
or Suboxone is long-acting,

485
00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:49.773
your transdermal buprenorphine or fentanyl.

486
00:25:51.660 --> 00:25:54.780
In order to safely use long-acting opioids,

487
00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:57.450
your patients should be opioid tolerant first.

488
00:25:57.450 --> 00:25:59.640
That means they're on opioids at least

489
00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:03.240
for a week at a high enough dose so that they're tolerant.

490
00:26:03.240 --> 00:26:06.993
Then you don't risk the problem of an overdose.

491
00:26:08.400 --> 00:26:11.760
Don't cut those sustained-release tablets.

492
00:26:11.760 --> 00:26:16.760
Don't cut a patch or you risk overdosing your patient.

493
00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:24.510
At times, you'll switch from one opioid to another.

494
00:26:24.510 --> 00:26:26.070
Maybe it's formulary,

495
00:26:26.070 --> 00:26:29.220
maybe one is not effective or available.

496
00:26:29.220 --> 00:26:31.290
And it's nice to know if you're gonna switch

497
00:26:31.290 --> 00:26:34.590
how you can maintain the appropriate dose for your patient.

498
00:26:34.590 --> 00:26:37.020
And there are these opioid equianalgesic

499
00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:39.150
dosing tables out there.

500
00:26:39.150 --> 00:26:42.123
Don't memorize it, just get an app that has it.

501
00:26:42.960 --> 00:26:45.030
The board may ask you some questions

502
00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:47.010
including how to use this information

503
00:26:47.010 --> 00:26:49.590
if they give you a chart, and they may ask you

504
00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:54.090
about some commonly used agents that you should know about.

505
00:26:54.090 --> 00:26:57.210
And you probably should know that oral morphine

506
00:26:57.210 --> 00:26:59.820
30 milligrams is the same as 10 milligrams

507
00:26:59.820 --> 00:27:02.670
of parental morphine or 3:1.

508
00:27:02.670 --> 00:27:05.220
That's something we would use pretty often.

509
00:27:05.220 --> 00:27:09.720
To note that oxycodone is stronger than morphine orally.

510
00:27:09.720 --> 00:27:12.330
So 20 milligrams of oxycodone is the same thing

511
00:27:12.330 --> 00:27:14.703
as 30 milligrams of morphine.

512
00:27:15.540 --> 00:27:18.510
That Lortab, Vicodin, hydrocodone,

513
00:27:18.510 --> 00:27:20.410
about the same thing as oral morphine.

514
00:27:21.420 --> 00:27:24.210
That Dilaudid is much stronger,

515
00:27:24.210 --> 00:27:26.250
almost three to four times as strong

516
00:27:26.250 --> 00:27:28.233
as morphine, if not more so.

517
00:27:29.370 --> 00:27:31.350
Dilaudid is a particularly decent agent

518
00:27:31.350 --> 00:27:33.720
for patients in renal failure, by the way.

519
00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:36.630
But morphine is not a good analgesic in renal failure

520
00:27:36.630 --> 00:27:38.763
because metabolites that buildup.

521
00:27:39.960 --> 00:27:41.850
Here's the CDCs table.

522
00:27:41.850 --> 00:27:43.833
Again, just find one that you can use.

523
00:27:45.210 --> 00:27:47.160
if you're going to switch opioids,

524
00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:49.590
again, use the tables to help you.

525
00:27:49.590 --> 00:27:52.530
If you're switching for formulary reasons,

526
00:27:52.530 --> 00:27:55.130
then when you switch, use a reduce dose

527
00:27:55.130 --> 00:27:58.890
of the second agent to avoid possible toxicity.

528
00:27:58.890 --> 00:28:00.840
If you're changing because the first thing

529
00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:04.734
isn't working real well, then don't reduce it even further

530
00:28:04.734 --> 00:28:07.983
and that kind of patient use an equal analgesic dose.

531
00:28:09.420 --> 00:28:12.750
Long term opioid therapy, your long-acting agents

532
00:28:12.750 --> 00:28:15.000
are very helpful and reasonable.

533
00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:17.580
They give you a stable blood level.

534
00:28:17.580 --> 00:28:21.330
Typically, 12.5 microgram fentanyl patch

535
00:28:21.330 --> 00:28:24.420
is like 30 milligrams a day of oral morphine.

536
00:28:24.420 --> 00:28:26.130
And a patches can be used in patients

537
00:28:26.130 --> 00:28:27.930
who can't take their own medicine,

538
00:28:27.930 --> 00:28:29.670
can be applied by a caregiver,

539
00:28:29.670 --> 00:28:32.220
hopefully onto the patient and not onto themselves.

540
00:28:33.480 --> 00:28:35.820
Fentanyl and buprenorphine patches,

541
00:28:35.820 --> 00:28:38.550
don't use 'em if the patient's not opioid tolerant.

542
00:28:38.550 --> 00:28:42.210
Don't use 'em for acute pain or acute post-op pain

543
00:28:42.210 --> 00:28:44.520
or intermittent pain, and take it off

544
00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:47.100
before you put the patient through an MRI machine.

545
00:28:47.100 --> 00:28:49.320
It has a little bit of metal backing

546
00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:52.120
and you'll fry the patient's skin if you're not careful.

547
00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:56.610
Which the following is correct?

548
00:28:56.610 --> 00:28:58.377
One should avoid prescribing opioids

549
00:28:58.377 --> 00:29:00.660
and benzos concurrently.

550
00:29:00.660 --> 00:29:02.910
Withdrawal symptoms are not seen

551
00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:06.510
by stopping long-acting opioids like methadone.

552
00:29:06.510 --> 00:29:11.280
Miosis, small pupils, is noted during opioid withdrawal.

553
00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:13.200
And opioid withdrawal precipitated

554
00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:16.020
by opioid antagonists like Narcan,

555
00:29:16.020 --> 00:29:18.573
typically severe and often life-threatening.

556
00:29:23.820 --> 00:29:25.800
And you got this one right too.

557
00:29:25.800 --> 00:29:29.790
Avoid opioids and benzos concurrently.

558
00:29:29.790 --> 00:29:33.630
Opioid guideline number seven, evaluate your benefits

559
00:29:33.630 --> 00:29:35.853
and risks after starting opioids.

560
00:29:36.870 --> 00:29:38.673
Look at those risks carefully.

561
00:29:39.510 --> 00:29:44.510
And those risks include side effects including constipation,

562
00:29:44.580 --> 00:29:48.570
respiratory, depression, sedation, edema,

563
00:29:48.570 --> 00:29:51.840
itching, may not be allergy, just a side effect.

564
00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:54.150
Opioid-induced hyperalgesia.

565
00:29:54.150 --> 00:29:56.040
Pain gets worse on opioids.

566
00:29:56.040 --> 00:29:57.630
How do you know that's happening?

567
00:29:57.630 --> 00:30:00.813
You stop it or reduce it and the pain gets better.

568
00:30:01.950 --> 00:30:05.460
Be careful about opioids and benzos together.

569
00:30:05.460 --> 00:30:10.143
Same thing with opioids and other CNS depressants like TCAs.

570
00:30:11.490 --> 00:30:14.280
If you're worried about your patient overdosing,

571
00:30:14.280 --> 00:30:16.170
then look at naloxone.

572
00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:18.150
You can prescribe it and many of the pharmacies

573
00:30:18.150 --> 00:30:19.690
can do without your consent

574
00:30:20.670 --> 00:30:22.890
and it's a good idea for some patients.

575
00:30:22.890 --> 00:30:26.103
In the medical setting, we give Narcan IV or IM.

576
00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.670
It's available for patients as an autoinjector

577
00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:31.293
or as a nasal spray.

578
00:30:34.260 --> 00:30:37.560
Nalmefone, also similar to Narcan.

579
00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:39.543
Also available, but very expensive.

580
00:30:41.250 --> 00:30:44.610
Opioid withdrawal happens when you stop an opioid

581
00:30:44.610 --> 00:30:48.390
or you give a partial agonist, agonist-antagonist,

582
00:30:48.390 --> 00:30:50.853
or a pure antagonist like Narca.

583
00:30:51.900 --> 00:30:54.900
Begin six to 12 hours after the last dose

584
00:30:54.900 --> 00:30:57.180
and persist for several days.

585
00:30:57.180 --> 00:31:00.570
24 to 40 hours after you stop methadone.

586
00:31:00.570 --> 00:31:03.330
To give Narcan, you stop immediately.

587
00:31:03.330 --> 00:31:05.850
Lasts for about 48 hours.

588
00:31:05.850 --> 00:31:07.980
How do you know a patient's withdrawing?

589
00:31:07.980 --> 00:31:10.380
Well, they'll tell you quickly.

590
00:31:10.380 --> 00:31:12.960
Nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain,

591
00:31:12.960 --> 00:31:15.690
myalgias, anxiety, restlessness.

592
00:31:15.690 --> 00:31:17.640
They don't look real good and they'll tell you

593
00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:19.860
they don't feel very good.

594
00:31:19.860 --> 00:31:24.860
Big pupils, yawning, tachycardia, hyper, hypotension.

595
00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:27.510
They don't feel well.

596
00:31:27.510 --> 00:31:28.950
How do you treat 'em?

597
00:31:28.950 --> 00:31:33.810
If you had stopped withdraw, 'em from an opioid over time,

598
00:31:33.810 --> 00:31:37.200
and the withdrawing, you can give 'em the opioid back again

599
00:31:37.200 --> 00:31:38.910
or you can give 'em some clonidine.

600
00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:41.490
Use benzos for nausea, antibiotics

601
00:31:41.490 --> 00:31:43.563
for nausea and vomiting as well.

602
00:31:44.850 --> 00:31:47.670
But if you gave Narcan and they withdrew,

603
00:31:47.670 --> 00:31:49.380
it's hard to tell how much of an opioid

604
00:31:49.380 --> 00:31:51.270
to give 'em back again.

605
00:31:51.270 --> 00:31:53.970
Then you might want to use things more like clonidine.

606
00:31:55.290 --> 00:31:56.460
There are some definitions

607
00:31:56.460 --> 00:31:58.200
you might wanna know for the boards.

608
00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:01.590
Tolerance, physical dependence, addiction,

609
00:32:01.590 --> 00:32:04.770
and pseudo-addiction are often found.

610
00:32:04.770 --> 00:32:08.100
Tolerance is when you use a drug for a long time,

611
00:32:08.100 --> 00:32:12.090
it takes more of that drug to get the same effect.

612
00:32:12.090 --> 00:32:15.030
Physical dependence, they've been on drug for a long time,

613
00:32:15.030 --> 00:32:18.243
you stop it abruptly and they have withdrawal symptoms.

614
00:32:19.410 --> 00:32:23.640
Addiction is a chronic problem where patients use substances

615
00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:26.820
and new behaviors that are compulsive even in spite

616
00:32:26.820 --> 00:32:30.000
of continued harmful consequences.

617
00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:33.780
Pseudo addiction is behaviors of patients who are in pain

618
00:32:33.780 --> 00:32:35.850
who have not been treated adequately.

619
00:32:35.850 --> 00:32:38.430
You treat them better, the symptoms go away.

620
00:32:38.430 --> 00:32:40.683
But this is kind of a controversial thing.

621
00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:45.420
Be wary of your patients who are forging prescriptions,

622
00:32:45.420 --> 00:32:49.110
using illicit drugs, the dog ate it, I need more.

623
00:32:49.110 --> 00:32:51.270
They're selling it on the street.

624
00:32:51.270 --> 00:32:53.730
Those are aberrant behaviors.

625
00:32:53.730 --> 00:32:57.210
For those patients, for those with opioid use disorders,

626
00:32:57.210 --> 00:32:58.710
they should be appropriately treated.

627
00:32:58.710 --> 00:33:01.620
If that's not you, then somebody in your community

628
00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:03.813
that you feel will do a good job for them.

629
00:33:05.070 --> 00:33:06.900
Our last question, which of

630
00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:09.090
the following statements is true?

631
00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:12.630
Pain management agreements that has informed consent

632
00:33:12.630 --> 00:33:14.790
and treatment agreements have been proven

633
00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:17.493
to dramatically decrease addiction.

634
00:33:18.450 --> 00:33:20.460
They have been recommended for all

635
00:33:20.460 --> 00:33:22.590
chronic opioid saving patients

636
00:33:22.590 --> 00:33:25.620
by the Federation of State Medical Boards.

637
00:33:25.620 --> 00:33:28.560
They typically mandate regularly scheduled as opposed

638
00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:32.190
to periodic drug testing and synthetic

639
00:33:32.190 --> 00:33:36.210
and semisynthetic opioids like oxycodone, fentanyl,

640
00:33:36.210 --> 00:33:40.020
methadone are usually detected by simple

641
00:33:40.020 --> 00:33:43.413
office-based amino acid, urine drug testing.

642
00:33:48.780 --> 00:33:50.490
And you have voted for the second one,

643
00:33:50.490 --> 00:33:52.113
which is absolutely true.

644
00:33:53.940 --> 00:33:57.390
Again, opioid guidelines talk about risk, benefits,

645
00:33:57.390 --> 00:34:00.810
your responsibilities, the patient's responsibilities,

646
00:34:00.810 --> 00:34:04.470
and again, these agreements are recommended by experts

647
00:34:04.470 --> 00:34:06.600
including the boards, but there are no studies

648
00:34:06.600 --> 00:34:09.333
that show they're effective in reducing addiction.

649
00:34:10.350 --> 00:34:13.440
I put into your handout a link

650
00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:15.450
to the New Hampshire Medical Society.

651
00:34:15.450 --> 00:34:17.050
Anybody here from New Hampshire?

652
00:34:17.910 --> 00:34:21.633
but they do a good job for opioid prescribing resources.

653
00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:25.800
The informed consent part talks about risks and benefits,

654
00:34:25.800 --> 00:34:30.600
side effects, tolerance, misuse, and side effects.

655
00:34:30.600 --> 00:34:33.810
Particularly the treatment agreement is

656
00:34:33.810 --> 00:34:36.480
who's gonna prescribe the medicines?

657
00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:37.670
What the patient's responsibility

658
00:34:37.670 --> 00:34:41.220
of taking them and keeping them within themselves,

659
00:34:41.220 --> 00:34:43.353
how they might be started or stopped?

660
00:34:45.090 --> 00:34:48.990
Consider again, the risk and benefits of drug testing

661
00:34:48.990 --> 00:34:51.150
and they are recommended again.

662
00:34:51.150 --> 00:34:53.640
Your simple enzyme-linked immunoassays

663
00:34:53.640 --> 00:34:56.163
are quick but not always accurate.

664
00:34:57.480 --> 00:35:02.220
The GCMS, gas chromatography, mass spectrometry studies

665
00:35:02.220 --> 00:35:05.943
are much more accurate and can identify a specific drug.

666
00:35:07.020 --> 00:35:09.510
If you're doing standard urine drug testing,

667
00:35:09.510 --> 00:35:12.390
morphine and codeine are usually accurate.

668
00:35:12.390 --> 00:35:15.210
Things like oxycodone and fentanyl may not be found

669
00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:17.220
even if the patient's taking it,

670
00:35:17.220 --> 00:35:19.383
but you can check that with GCMS.

671
00:35:20.340 --> 00:35:21.990
Cocaine is usually accurate,

672
00:35:21.990 --> 00:35:24.960
but then 48 hours, no matter what the patient tells you,

673
00:35:24.960 --> 00:35:27.360
and they'll tell you a lot about that.

674
00:35:27.360 --> 00:35:28.740
Negative tests for benzos

675
00:35:28.740 --> 00:35:31.500
may not be accurate with recent use

676
00:35:31.500 --> 00:35:35.070
and there's a lot of cross-reactivity between amphetamines

677
00:35:35.070 --> 00:35:38.460
and things like pseudoephedrine, so be aware.

678
00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:40.470
When do you continue opioid therapy?

679
00:35:40.470 --> 00:35:44.460
When there's improvement, pain relief and function,

680
00:35:44.460 --> 00:35:48.270
lack of aberrant behaviors, lack of side effects.

681
00:35:48.270 --> 00:35:51.630
If you're seeing problems, taper them off.

682
00:35:51.630 --> 00:35:54.720
Discontinue them if you're getting illicit drug use,

683
00:35:54.720 --> 00:35:58.980
threatening behaviors to your staff, forgeries or overdoses.

684
00:35:58.980 --> 00:36:02.910
You can taper them gradually or rapidly if you need to.

685
00:36:02.910 --> 00:36:04.683
Gradually is much more humane.

686
00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:09.630
Unless there are signs of life-threatening issues,

687
00:36:09.630 --> 00:36:14.310
again gradually rather than abruptly reduce opioid doses.

688
00:36:14.310 --> 00:36:16.650
Who goes to a pain specialist?

689
00:36:16.650 --> 00:36:20.220
When you're on high dose of morphine equivalence,

690
00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:24.334
abuse or drug-related issues, failure to comply

691
00:36:24.334 --> 00:36:26.970
with a number of trials of treatment,

692
00:36:26.970 --> 00:36:30.000
those who need invasive therapies that you can't give,

693
00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.850
often those who need behavioral therapies.

694
00:36:32.850 --> 00:36:36.060
I hope this information's helpful for you in the boards

695
00:36:36.060 --> 00:36:37.710
and in the care of your patients.

